Modern cryptography is fundamentally concerned with the problem of secure private communication. A Secret Key Exchange is a protocol where Alice and Bob, having no secret information in common to start, are able to agree on 
a common secret key, conversing over a public channel. The notion of a Se­cret Key Exchange protocol was first introduced in the seminal paper of Diffie and Hellman [


 1

]. [


 1

] presented a concrete implementation of a Secret Key Ex­change protocol, dependent on a specific assumption (a variant on the discrete log), specially tailored to yield Secret Key Exchange. Secret Key Exchange is of course trivial if trapdoor permutations exist. However, there is no known implementation based on a weaker general assumption.

